LAW NOTICES.—This Day.

COURT OF CHANCERY, LINCOLN'S INN.
Sittings at ten.

Tamlyn v Reynolds, motion by order—Ex parte Allen, petition by order.

Motions continued.

VICE CHANCELLOR'S COURT, LINCOLN'S INN.
Sittings at ten.

Warren v Burton, motion by order—Taylor v Fieldes, ditto—Attorney-General v Pearson, part heard—Attorney-General v Stewart, part heard—Sherratt v Sherratt, petition by order—Allsop v Towgood, petition by order—Raybould v Durant, cause by order—Spicer v Whitwell, by order—Colley v Colley, petition by order.—In re Dovenby Hospital, ditto—Meagoe v Hodson, exceptions, part heard—Meagoe v Newton, plea—Newman v West, demurrer—Kelshaw v Galway—Ditto v ditto—Morgan v Howell.

ROLLS' COURT, CHANCERY-LANE.
Sittings at ten.

Moggeridge v Woodruff, judgment—In re Morgan, petition—Majendle v Mounsey, part heard—Sayle v Shackles—West v Shuttleworth—Greenway v Rotherham—Turner v Rawlison, exceptions—Smith v Wyatt—Hiller v Hiller—Stafford v Stafford—Attorney-General v Barham—Pilkington v Bright—Barfoot v Chitty, ditto—Pratt v Tucker.

COURT OF KING'S BENCH.
Sitting at half-past nine.

London Common Juries.—Driver and Another v Ellis—Ewins v Matthews—Simpson v Crawcour—Utherne and Another v Collinghi and Another—Knight v Waterman.

COURT OF COMMON PLEAS.
Sittings at half-past nine.

London Common Juries—Salmon v Cranston—Passenger v Brookes—Shirley v Jacobs—Wise v Downes—Simpson v Russ.

The Court of King's Bench, and the Court of Common Pleas, will adjourn this day, till Easter term. The Court of Exchequer adjourned yesterday. The business in the Court of King's Bench, standing over till next term, consists of only eighteen causes, nine in Middlesex, and nine in London. In the Court of Common Pleas there is an arrear of seven special jury causes in Middlesex, and twenty special and common jury causes in London.

BANKRUPTCY COURT, BANGHALL STREET.
Before Mr. Commissioner FANE.—Stephen King, of Kinnerton-street, Knightsbridge, baker, at ten; choice of assignees—John Barnett, of Tottenham-street, Fitzroy square, copperplate-printer, at eleven; adjourned examination.

Before Mr. Commissioner Holroyd.—H. D. Eggleton, of Charles-street, Trevor-square, Brompton, coal-merchant, at two; adjourned examination—Stephenson and Blunt, of Great Ormond-street, Queen-square, surveyors, at twelve; adjourned examination.

On the Ground Floor.—In Henry Rain's bankruptcy, at eleven; creditors to meet the assignees.
